    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1"><text styleclass="Heading1" translate="true">Querying the Capabilities of a Data Source</text></para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Your </text><text styleclass="Class Name" translate="true">DBConnection</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> instance is your entry point to the sample database. There are quite a few public methods available for this object. Why not locate the </text><text styleclass="Class Name" translate="true">DBConnection</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> class in the </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Class Browser</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> and take a look at the methods in the </text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">public</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> category. You can use a number of these to query the capabilities of the ODBC driver and underlying database engine. Try the displaying the result of sending following public accessing messages:</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">c dbmsName. &quot;Display it&quot;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">c dbmsVer. &quot;Display it&quot;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">c databaseName. &quot;Display it&quot;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">c readOnly. &quot;Display it&quot;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">c numericFunctions. &quot;Display it&quot;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">c autoCommit. &quot;Display it&quot;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
